Indicators of the problem
Singapore produces a great amount of electronic product consumption in Singapore. As the report pointed out (Chua, 2003), shopping has become a major activity in Singaporeans' leisure time. Such a trend of consumerism has been promoted by planned obsolescence means that products have been designed to have a limited lifetime (Orbach, 2004). It has been decided at a very early stage how long it is designed to last. Companies use materials like soft metals and plastics so that they become unworkable soon through normal usage. In such a way, people need to replace and buy their electronic products again soon. Perceived obsolescence refers to the phenomenon that consumers will follow the latest generation of electronic product consumption and low recycling rate of electronic waste, and evaluate the current situations and measures in East and Southeast Asia, by S. Honda, D. S. Khetriwal & R. Kuehr, p. 60. Copyright 2016 by the United Nations University.
